<p>Thanks for your sharing the detail steps, I can reproduce the issue through your shared steps and this issue has been escalated for further investigation, if there is any process, I will inform you immediately.</p>

**Version Used**: VS 17.14.21 .NET 9.0.11 Preview language features (Also VS 18, .NET 10)

I have a custom error type where I use null to indicate success.
```
public static bool IsSuccess([NotNullWhen(false)] this MyErrorClass? info)
{
    return info is null;
}
```
With the new C# 14 features, I wanted to change this to a property.
```
extension(MyErrorClass? info)
{
    public bool IsSuccess
    {
        [NotNullWhen(false)] // CS0592 error here
        get => info is null;
    }
}
```
With the new extension properties, it is now possible to write a property that runs on a null object.  So, null analysis should be updated to support this.

**Expected Behavior**:
Some way to tell the null analysis that the extended class is not null given some property return value.

**Actual Behavior**:
It is not possible to change from an extension method to an extension property while preserving the null analysis.

**Version Used**: .NET 10.0.0, VS 18.0.2

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```C#
public struct MyStruct
{
    public static implicit operator Span<byte>(in MyStruct value) => default;
}

static void CSharpV13(MyStruct x)
{
    // Ok.
    // Implicit conversion MyStruct -> Span<byte>.
    M_Span(x);

    // Does not compile.
    // C# 13 cannot do implicit conversion MyStruct -> Span<byte> -> ROS<byte>.
    M_ReadOnlySpan(x);

    // Ok.
    // Uses implicit conversion MyStruct -> Span<byte> and calls M(Span<byte>) overload.
    M(x);
}

static void CSharpV14(MyStruct x)
{
    // Ok.
    // Implicit conversion MyStruct -> Span<byte>.
    M_Span(x);

    // Ok.
    // C# 14 does implicit conversion MyStruct -> Span<byte> -> ROS<byte>.
    M_ReadOnlySpan(x);

    // Not sure if this is ok.
    // It's definitely a behavioral change compared to C# 13.
    // Uses implicit conversion MyStruct -> Span<byte> -> ROS<byte> and calls M(ROS<byte>) overload.
    M(x);
}

static void M_Span(Span<byte> s) { }
static void M_ReadOnlySpan(ReadOnlySpan<byte> s) { }

static void M(Span<byte> s) { }
static void M(ReadOnlySpan<byte> s) { }
```

I looked for a more detailed description of the changes to span conversions in C# 14, but I haven't found anything related to this particular situation.

Right now, it looks like a bug to me.

If it's not a bug (could you please explain why?), then it's solvable by the newly added `OverloadResolutionPriority` attribute. Priority of `M(Span<byte> s)` overload can be increased, and then it works in C# 14 as in C# 13:
```csharp
[OverloadResolutionPriority(1)]
static void M(Span<byte> s) { }

static void M(ReadOnlySpan<byte> s) { }
```

Also, if it's not a bug, I believe such a priority increase should be added to `MemoryMarshal.AsRef<T>(Span<T>)` via `[OverloadResolutionPriority]`. The example below shows why:
```C#
static void CSharpV13(MyStruct x)
{
    // Ok. Overload AsRef<byte>(Span<byte>) is selected.
    ref var r = ref MemoryMarshal.AsRef<byte>(x);
}

static void CSharpV14(MyStruct x)
{
    // Does not compile. Overload AsRef<byte>(ReadOnlySpan<byte>) is selected, so `ref var` cannot be used.
    ref var r = ref MemoryMarshal.AsRef<byte>(x);

    // Compiles, but that's not what i need.
    ref readonly var r2 = ref MemoryMarshal.AsRef<byte>(x);
}
```

The compiler hard-codes in that a ref-struct collection expression that implements IEnumerable has 'local scope'.  This was hardcoded in because originally this was just an error (it used to not be legal to have a ref-struct implementing an interface).

For example, the following is legal:

```c#
ref struct R : IEnumerable
{
    public void Add(int x) { }

    // implementation of IEnumerable...
}
```

Now that that's legal we need to properly do the analysis here.  The analysis of `R r = [with(...), x, y, .. z]` is complex.  Basically,  it should be hte intersection of the ref-safety of hte call to the constructor that `with(...)` defers to, along with the ref-safety of all the `.Add` calls that are made for `.Add(x)`, `.Add(y)`, `foreach (var v in z) .Add(v)`.

This is challenging as the determination of what .Add methods are called is deferred till lowering.
